<DOC><DOCNO> AP880901-0065 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-88 0608EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Jews     09-01 0195</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Soviet-Jews,0201</SECOND><HEAD>Emigration Highest Since May 1980, Armenian Emigration Drops</HEAD><DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Jewish emigration from the Soviet Union reached anew eight-year high in August, with a total of 1,864 Jews allowedto leave the country, the agency helping them resettle said today.   But the number of Armenians permitted to emigrate from theSoviet Union dropped to 223 in August from 1,018 in the previousmonth, the Intergovernmental Committee for Migration said.   Spokeswoman Regina Boucault had no explanation for the drop. Shesaid that so far this year 8,241 Armenians have been allowed toleave.   The Jewish emigres represented the eighth straight monthlyincrease in the number of arrivals at the Vienna, Austria, transitcenter, Ms. Boucault said. Only 116 emigres opted to go to Israel.   The August figure was the highest since May 1980, when 1,976Soviet Jews were allowed to emigrate, Ms. Boucault said. Theeight-month total for 1988 is now at 9,560 emigres, of whom 1,046went to Israel.   The largest official exodus, 51,330, was recorded in 1979 beforethe Soviet intervention in Afghanistan chilled East-West relations.   Almost 270,000 Soviet Jews have emigrated since the resettlementprogram started in 1971.</TEXT></DOC>